items.synopsis: A No vote is recorded nationally and in all six states as the Voice to Parliament proposal is defeated in Australia's first referendum this century. Follow all the results with our live blog.

title.children: PM says nation must seek 'new way forward' after voters in all six states reject Voice to Parliament

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Voice has been rejected by voters in all Australian states. After less than an hour of counting, the ABC now projects the Voice has been defeated in Western Australia. The referendum has also failed to gain a majority of voters nationally. The ACT was the only jurisdiction to vote Yes.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Opposition Leader Peter Dutton is speaking now. "It is clear, obviously, that the referendum has not been successful, and I think that is good for our country," he says. "I want to say a very special thank you tonight to Jacinta Price, to Warren Mundine. No-one is owed more gratitude than each of these individuals. "They have led the No case, they have suffered through deeply personal and offensive attacks. I want to say thank you very much to David Littleproud and all of my Coalition colleagues."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Smartraveller has just confirmed that Australian repatriation flights that were scheduled to leave Tel Aviv today will not depart. Here's the statement: The situation is highly challenging and rapidly changing. Unfortunately, we have been advised our scheduled flights will not depart Israel today. A further flight will not depart as scheduled tomorrow. The Australian government is working to ensure Australians who want to leave can do so as soon as possible. We will communicate to registered Australians about next available flights. Australians in Israel or the Occupied Palestinian Territories should register via https://crisis.dfat.gov.au/crisisportal/s/ or by calling the 24-hour Consular Emergency Centre on +61 2 6261 3305 (from overseas) or 1300 555 135 (from Australia).

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Australia will provide an initial $10 million in humanitarian assistance for civilians affected by the conflict in Gaza. That will be split between $3 million through the International Committee of the Red Cross to fund "urgent needs like restoring essential services and providing medical support to victims of the conflict" and $7 million through United Nations agencies providing critical aid. The UN support will include emergency water supplies, nutrition, sanitation and hygiene services and child protection. The Gaza Strip has been cut off from food, water and fuel supplies coming through Israel, with electricity also cut and several health facilities damaged in air strikes. "We have seen devastating loss of innocent life since the heinous attacks on Israel by brutal terrorist group Hamas," Foreign Minister Penny Wong said. "Far from representing the Palestinian people, Hamas undermines Palestinian needs and aspirations. "We continue to call for the unconditional release of all hostages. We stand with Israel and reiterate its right to defend itself. "President Biden has called on Israel to operate by the rules of war in its response to Hamas attacks â€” we join him and others in that call. "We call for safe and unimpeded humanitarian access to civilians affected by the worsening humanitarian crisis in Gaza. "We call for the establishment of a corridor to enable humanitarian needs to be met. And we support the work of the United States, Egypt and others towards this goal. "Adherence to international humanitarian law must be prioritised â€” including the protection of civilians, wherever they live."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Australia announces $10 million in aid for civilians in Gaza
